{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lagarde_ver02/data/sn92073203/00332893087/1945101101/0339.xml":{"full_text":"THURSDAY, OCT. 11, 1945\nBrief Review Os State, National And World News During The Past Week\nGENERAL NIMITZ *IS\nGIVEN HERO\u2019S WELCOME\nWashington\u2014The nation\u2019s capi\ntal this week thundered a well\ndone to Admiral Chester W. Nim\nitz, who fashioned the world\u2019s\ngreatest fleet from the shambles\nof Pearl Harbor and led it to vic\ntory in Tokyo bay.\nHumbly accepting a hero\u2019s wel\ncome accorded by President Tru\nman, congress and a cheering\ncrowd of more than 1.000,000, the\nwhite-haired Texan warned that\nnever again must the nation be\ncaught unprepared.\n\u201cI pray that we pledge our\nselves to remain strong in order\nthat we may continue to live as\nfree men,\u201d he said.\n-He reminded a joint session of\ncongress of the grim price paid\nfor unprepardedness in this war\n\u2014\u201cthe men who will forever\nsleep beneath the lonely palms of\nuncounted Pacific isles, men who\nwill stand their eternal watch at\nsea as long as time goes on.\u201d\nU. S. JUSTICE JACKSON\nAT NAZIS TRIALS NOW\nBerlin Justice Robert H.\nJackson and his staff arrived by\nplane from Wiesbaden this week\nfor preliminary sessions of the\ninternational war crimes tribunal\npreparatory to the proclamation\nof indictments against top Nazi\nleaders to be tried at Nuernberg.\nJackson is the American prose\ncutor. French and Soviet mem\nbers of the tribunal previously\nhad arrived and part of the Brit\nish commission was here. The\njudges met Monday to pre\nindictments which was held on\nTuesday.\nTHE\nParkway\nTHEATER\nWest Jefferson. N. C.\nFRI.-SAT. OCT. 12-13\nMatinee Every Saturday\n12:30 P. M.\nJane Frazee\nHoosier Hot Shots\nand Others\n\u2014in\u2014\nSWING IN THE SADDLE\nChapter 7\n\u201cManhunt of Mvstery\nisland\u201d\nAlso Comedy\nMON. ONLY OCT. 15\nIda Lupino\nWilliam Prince\nSydney Greenstreet\n\u2014in\u2014\nPILLOW TO POST\nAlso Short Subjects\nTUES. ONLY OCT. 16\nEric Von Stroheim\nMary Beth Hughes\n\u2014in\u2014\nTHE GREAT FLAMARION\nChapter 12\n\u201cMonster and the Ape\u201d\nAlso Short Subjects\nWED.-THURS. OCT. 17-18\nMatinee Every Thurs. 1:00\nKEEP YOUR POWDER\nDRY\nstarring\nLana Turner\nLaraine Day\nSusan Peters\nLatest News\nAn Appeal To The Farmers\nTHE WAR IS OVER, THANK GOD. Now let us\nwin the PEACE with the same determination, courage\nand unanimous effort. Difficulties and some hardships\nmust be faced and overcome during the Reconversion\nPeriod. Competition will be keener and prices of many\ncommodities are bound to be lower and quality better.\nWe will get more value for our dollar. Our industry will\nnot be an exception to the rule. In the near future, more\nshipping facilities will be available and Briarwood from\nEurope will arrive in ever increasing quantity. This may\nforce a downward trend of prices for Ivy and Laurel.\nWe are not afraid of competition. We have produced\npipe blocks all of our lives and will continue to produce\nthem. But we have no control over prices. Therefore,\nwe suggest that you dig your Ivy and Laurel NOW while\nprices are at their peak. We ask your cooperation to dig\ngood and solid burls. We have no use for stumpy or\ndead wood. Help us avoid the unpleasant task of culling\nbad stools.\nCarolina Briar Corporation\nWest Jefferson, North Carolina\nDarnell Brothers Are In Service\nJmilr\nlilt oF Iw\nIljF I hbKI\nWerth Darnell, S-IC, left, and Pfc. Clarence Darnell,\nright, sons of Mr. and Mrs. Ess Darnell, of Glendale Springs.\nSeaman Darnell recently returned from the Pacific and wears\nfour battle Stars. Pfc. Darnell served 18 months overseas and\nis now stationed in the Philippines.\nReconversion Is Expected To\nBe Speeded Up In Most Towns\nI\nMENTAL HOSPITAL TO\nBE READY OCTOBER 15\nRaleigh\u2014State Senator Thom\nas O\u2019Berry of Goldsboro, a mem\nber of the State hospitals board\nof control, said here that the\nstate\u2019s new mental hospital at\nCamp Sutton would be ready to\nI receive patients by October 15.\nI Patients will be transferred\nthere from the Raleigh and Mor\n'ganton hospitals, he said, and by\nI the first of next year the Sutton\nhospital would be operating at\ncapacity.\n\u201cWe should be able to relieve\nthe acute space shortage at the\ni Raleigh and Morganton units by\nithe first of the year, and be\nready to handle new patients at\nboth 4these institutions,\u201d O\u2019Berry\nsaid. He added that no new pa\ntients would be taken in at the\nSutton hospital. The space pro\nvided by the transfer of old' pa-\nItients to Sutton will be used to\n{take care of new patients.\ni The Camp Sutton hospital was\nI leased frorry the army. Approxi-\nI mately 500 patients will be treat\njed there when the unit begins\noperating at capacity.\nHITLER IS STILL\nREPORTED TO BE ALIVE\nLondon\u2014Gen. Eisenhower was\nreported by the Dutch radio to\nhave told Dutch newspapermen\nthere was \u201creason to believe\u201d\nthat Hitler was still alive.\nThe broadcast, recorded by\ni BBC. said that one of the corre\nspondents. accompanying Eisen\nj hower on a visit to the Hague\nasked the general if he thought\nHitler was dead.\n\u201cI thought so at first.\u201d Eisen\nhower was said to have replied,\n\u201cbut there is reason to believe\nthat he is still alive. But that in\nl itself does not constitute a prob\nlem.\u201d\nN. C. UNEMPLOYMENT\nSHOWING DECLINE\nRaleigh\u2014A gradual decline in\nunemployment in North Carolina\nwas revealed by the state unem-\nployment compensation commis\ni sion. which said there had been\nfewer claimants for jobless pay\nI Washington\u2014After surveying\nbusiness leaders in nearly 900 ci-\nI ties, the committee for economic\ndevelopment reported this week\nthat \u201creconversion may proceed\nvery rapidly.\u201d\nSixty out of 84 large cities and\n1 war production centers advised\nthat they \u201cdo not expect grave\nI unemployment problems\u201d in\nshifting to peacetime production,\nsaid CED, nationwide business\norganization.\nAsked whether the survey bol\nstered hopes of hitting CED\u2019s re- j\nconversion goal of 53 to 56 mil\nlion higher than in pre-war 1940.\n1 \u2014Walter D. Fuller, president of j\nthe Curtis Publishing company, i\ntold a news conference:\n\u201cAs far as I am personally con-1\ncerned. my confidence is greatly\namplified.\u201d\nFuller, who is chairman of\nCED\u2019s field development division,\nsaid that a \u201cgrass roots\u201d survey\nof 800 smaller cities and towns\ntaken by telegraph supported the\nreports from large cities.\nTwenty-five of the large cen\nters show reconversion \u201cwell un\nder way with no major unem\n-1 ployment problems indicated,\u201d\nsaid the report.\n\u201cThree cities will require a\nj three-month period, 20 cities six\nmonths, and 12 a year for full re\nconversion.\u201d\n\u201cIn spite of needing time for\nreconversion these cities do not\ni expect grave unemployment prob\ni lems.\u201d\nI\nTen cities could not foresee the\n.'rehiring of all their jobless per\nsons; thirteen lacked data to es\ntimate the time required for full\nreconversion, and one foresaw\nits peak of joblessness in 1947.\nj\nI School Age Boys\nNot To Be Drafted\n\n18 And 19 Year-olds To Be\nAllowed To Finish School\nYear\nIt was announced this week by\nMrs. L. J. Yelanjian, chief clerk\n'of the draft board, that the se\nlective service regulations now\nprovide that the induction of high\nschool students may be postponed.\nAnv person 18 or 19 years of age,\nwhile attending high school or a\nsimilar institution of learning,\nwho is ordered to report before\nthe academic year is over, may\nbe granted the privilege of fin\nishing the academic year.\nThe new regulation further\nstates that any person who has\nnot reached the age of 18 years\nand who is ordered to report for\ninduction may upon his request,\nhave his induction postponed un\ntil graduation, or until he ceases\nto pursue continuously and sat\nisfactorily a course of instruction,\nor until he arrives at the age of\n20 jiears.\nPotato salad and cole slaw may\nbe pepped up with \u201chot dressing\u201d\ninstead of cold, say Extension\nhome economists at State College,\neach week since the middle of\nSeptember,\nCol. A. L. Fletcher, UCC chair\nman, said the largest number of\nunemployed workers receiving\njobless benefit checks at any one\n.time was listed during the week\n(of September 15/ when 7,161\nworkers drew checks. Os these,\n5,725 were women.\nFletcher said that last week the\nnumber dropped to 6;711 unem\nployed, of. whom 5,104 were wom\nen claimants.\nHIE SKYLAND POST, WEST JEFFERSON, N. C.\ni\nI TODAY I\nand I\nTOMORROW\nBy DON ROBINSON\u2019 J\nCONFLICT groups\nPerhaps the one thing we must\nguard against most, in putting this\nhumpty-dumpty world back to\ngether again, is to avoid building\nup group antagonism.\nIf a Russian makes a speech\nwhich angers us. we must not con\nclude that his remarks are repre\nsentative of all Russians.\nIf a labor leader stirs our\nwrath by calling a strike for\nsome petty cause, we must not\nassume that all laborers, or\nall members of his union, are\nto be condemmed.\nIf the head of a manufac\nturing concern attempts to re\nduce the earnings of his em\nployees. we mustn\u2019t jump to\nthe conclusion that all indus\ntrial leaders are \u201cout to get\u201d\nlabor.\nIf one company or one union\ngoes in for race discrimination, we\nmust not assume that others are\nplanning similiar discrimination.\nMost of us are much too prone\nto condemn a group because of\nthe actions of a few individual\nmembers of that group. On the\ninternational front such an atti\ntude leads inevitably to warfare.\nAnd on the domestic front it\ncauses wide splits in our national\nunity which do irreparable dam\nage and result in conflicts that\ncannot help but delay our nation\u2019s\nprogress.\nLABOR management\nIt is going to be difficult, if not\nimpossible, to wipe out some of\nthe group antagonism which has\na real hold on our people\u2014par\nticularly that which exists be\ntween labor and management.\nThere are undoubtedly many\nindustrial managers who are so\nincensed against labor unions that\ntheir natural reaction is one of\nkeen enjoyment as they contem\nplate the possibility of being able\nDozens and Dozens of\n.New Living Room\nSUITES\nMOHAIR VELOUR TAPESTRY\nW I Assorted patterns to choose from. These are all beauti-\n1 su tes All are real values, too. See them before you\nbuy.\n97.50 to 189.50\nPIANOS\nFiber Board 5 Beautiful pianos with wonderful tones. We now\nhave a good selection to choose from.\nHurry, Hurry, while we still have plenty. 00 j.\nNew Shipment Os yi\n1 Mattresses\nKit h Rcillges Priced from $9 ,5 up\nThey are here those new postwar kitchen\nse l ec^on mattresses,\nranges you planned for. Roomy, beautiful, modern\nliL All are real values. Invest in\nand long lasting. All are wonderful values.\nrest in one or more of our\n39 ,5 tO s \u00df7\u2019 s A mattresses.\nSee Us For Bargains In All New And Used Furniture.\nWe Sell On Easy Terms See Us For Your Furniture\nBurgess Furniture Company\nWest Jefferson, N. C. NEW AND USED FURNITURE Boone, MC.\nGalax, Va. '.7' \u201cANTIQUES A SPECIALTY* Marion, Va.\nto put the screws on labor. During\nthe war, many of them will tell\nyou, they haven\u2019t been able to run\ntheir own businesses\u2014they have\nhad to put up with waste, inef\nficiency and super mollycoddling\niin order to keep the men oper\nj ating their plans.\nLabor leaders, on the other\nhand, know that with certain com\npanies the men would still be get\nting starvation wages if it wasn\u2019t\nfor the organized insistence on\nbetter conditions.\nBoth sides have strong cases\nand can give vivid examples\nto prove their point. But fair\nminded, unemotional analysis\nwill also show that there are\nmany labor leaders who do\nnot make excessive demands\nand there are many industrial\nleaders who would treat men\nfairly, and pay the highest\nwages they could, whether\ntheir workers were organized\nor whether they weren\u2019t.\nIn order to avoid conflict of\nclass against class and group\nagainst group, we must try to con\nsider each case individually. We\nmust try to stop blaming all labor\nfor the sins of some individual\nmembers of their group and we\nmust avoid blaming all manage\nment for the sharp practices of a\nfew industrialists.\nINDIVIDUALS varied\nA woman who lives in the coun\ntry visited Detroit. When she re\nturned she was asked at a local\nclub meeting to tell about her\ntrip. In telling of her experiences\nshe said, in a tone indicating that\nshe expected to shock her audi\nence, \u201cI met a man who was a\nmember of the United Automobile\nWorkers Union and you know,\nhe was really a very nice fellow.\u201d\nThere are plenty of people who\ndon\u2019t have much contact with\nindustrial communities who think\nthat all union members wear\nhorns. But if they met a sizable\ngroup of workers they would un\ndoubtedly come to the conclusion\nthat unions, like all other organ-\nI ized groups, include all types of\npeople and should not be judged\nas a group.\nI Similarly, the laborer who\nworks in a factory where the\nmanagement seems to have\nno interest in the welfare of\nj workers is apt to conclude\nthat all business management\nis \u201cthe enemy.\u201d But if he met\nwith a large group of business\nmen he would find that they\ntoo include all different types\n\u2014some of whom are fighting\nagainst labor and others who\nare more interested in the\nwelfare of their employees\nBring a bit of Home\nto the Homesick Yank\nWill w i JKnHnLf\ns\u00bb\nGIVE GENEROUSLY TO YOUR\nUnited War Fund\nDrive\nFAUCETTE\u2019S\nWEST JEFFERSON, N. C\nPAGE THREE\nthan in anything else.\nIf we are going to have a ttnitetL\nsmooth-running nation we must\nall try to stop taking side& And:\nthe very best way to avoid group*\nclashes is to avoid |hinking of peo\nple in terms of groups, but to\nthink of each group as a varied,\nassembly of individuals..","height":"27351","width":"20118"}}
